{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"2b1161c6-a2b2-4960-961d-f3d206de2b58","content":"Here's my analysis of the evaluation performance issues in this project:\n\n## MSBuild Evaluation Performance Issues\n\n### 1. 🔴 File I/O Property Function (Line 13, `EvalHeavy.csproj`)\n```xml\n<BuildNotes>$([System.IO.File]::ReadAllText('build-notes.txt'))</BuildNotes>\n```\n**Problem:** `System.IO.File::ReadAllText` performs synchronous disk I/O during the evaluation phase. This blocks the evaluator and runs on *every* evaluation (IDE design-time builds, restores, etc.). **Fix:** Move file reading to a target with `Inputs/Outputs` so it only runs at build time.\n\n### 2. 🟡 Broad Glob Pattern (Line 9)\n```xml\n<AdditionalFiles Include=\"**\\*.*\" Exclude=\"**\\bin\\**;**\\obj\\**\" />\n```\n**Problem:** `**\\*.*` walks the entire directory tree during evaluation. In larger repos this becomes expensive. Add the pattern to `DefaultItemExcludes` or narrow the glob scope to specific directories/extensions.\n\n### 3. 🟡 Deep Import Chain (3 levels)\n```\nEvalHeavy.csproj → level1.props → level2.props → level3.props\n```\n**Problem:** Each import adds evaluation overhead. While 3 levels is manageable today, this pattern can grow quickly. Flatten or consolidate where possible.\n\n---\n\n**Most impactful fix:** Remove the `File::ReadAllText` property function — it's the costliest pattern here since it forces disk I/O on every single evaluation pass.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"2ad61a4a-c836-42db-ad13-1dbffa6cfb96","outputTokens":393,"requestId":"7400:AB6AD:1D6A53C:2085473:6A052489"},"id":"10e10387-2f24-445a-b25e-a99cd9636b5e","timestamp":"2026-05-14T01:25:39.963Z","parentId":"4530296b-fbee-42bf-ba56-034249d08878"}
